metadata.name: Southern Gothic #9
metadata.description:
‚ÄúSouthern Gothic‚Äù is my debut release on the fxhash platform. The project is created entirely through code. All copyrights are released to the holder of each image output, even for commercial purposes.

‚ÄúSouthern Gothic‚Äù borrows its name from the literary genre made famous by writers like Flannery O‚ÄôConnor and Carson McCullers. Rather than illustrating a singular setting, the code generates an entire rural townscape, thereby, blurring the boundaries between representation and narrative. The individual scenes are framed frontally with an intentionally flat aesthetic character, referencing traditional folk art of the American South. The absence of human figures within these scenes adds to their overwhelming sense of darkness and forlorn. Observing multiple scenes side-by-side, one may even get the strange feeling that something terrible has happened (or is about to happen) in this rural landscape.

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: Nanopanorama #64
metadata.description:
Distorted noise with weird textures and funky shapes rendered using my rayhatcher algorithm.

4671 characters of pure Javascript, no libraries.

Some options can be changed via the URL:

&lw=.25 : The linewidth in millimetres.
&d=.4 : Line density (multiplier to linewidth).
&h=235 : Page height in millimetres. The aspect ratio is 16:9, for a width of 420mm, suitable for A3 plotting.
&bg=1 : Set to 0 to remove background rectangle (recommended for plotting).

When plotting, it is recommended to use a path reordering / optimizing tool such as axicli or vpype to greatly reduce the plotting time.

metadata.name: ProtoByte: Scyphozoa.01 #50
metadata.description:
Scyphozoa.01 is the alpha release built with my new ProtoByte.ts library.

ProtoByte is a Verlet Integration-based creative coding framework designed to simulate and render organic, aesthetic structures and behaviors. It combines physics simulation with artistic visualization, offering versatile tools for creating dynamic, whimsically lifelike forms and interactions in 3D.

ProtoByte.ts
Release notes:

As I begin to release #genart projects like Scyphozoa.01, and soon enough the ProtoByte.ts library itself, I thought it would be useful to share my thoughts and hopes for the project. 

I plan to vary minor and major releases in alignment with library development. This drop reflects a minor (though quite significant personally) internal release. Minor releases will generally have more affordable pricing and larger editions.

Project Goals:
1.  Release a fun, distinct and highly useable library, with advanced behavior for creative coding that supports existing core libs such as @threejs, @p5jsArt, @processingOrg, @babylonjs.

2. Develop and nurture a userbase that both create with and contribute to the overall ProtoByte.ts project.

3. Develop supporting pedagogy to continue my 30 year odyssey in #creativecoding. 

4. Continue to contribute to the mission for increased adoption, growth and value of Web3 as a major creative space/art marketplace.

metadata.name: Soft Cell #86
metadata.description:
This work is an homage to relief printmaking. Other artists have explored the kinship between generative art and print using pen plotters and silkscreen. This work attempts to take the concept of a relief print and apply it to a digital canvas.

This art work is produced in layers. For each layer the printing surface or matrix is defined by one set of algorithms. Another set of algorithms then applies the "ink" (imperfectly!) to the matrix. For each layer in turn the matrix is then applied to the canvas.

Press [s] to save a png image of the work.

The work renders at an economical 800x800px. Any edge size may be specified by adding &sz=x to the URL. A print of about 6 inches by 6 inches is recommended, &sz=1800 at 300dpi.

Rust/JS/WASM
Polygon SDF algorithm adapted from Inigo Quilez.

metadata.name: √âvasion #116
metadata.description:
This project is inspired by a familiar landscape.
 
It combines several things: a realistic dune landscape, minimalist ocean and sky, and a surrealist window at the centre.

The window deliberately presents a brighter ocean, where the sun is reflected, with waves and veils caught in the wind. It aims at representing what inspires us, what calms us, what makes us feel at home. This window extracts us from our daily thoughts and stress.


So I named this project "√âvasion", a French word, which could be translated as "Escape" in English.


In this project, I decided that, even though each output will be unique and will have its own features, it will be possible, in live mode, to show/hide some elements of the project. This will allow each one of you to adapt the project to what is most relevant to you and save it.

This does not change the unique features of your mint, but you can adapt it to your preferences, to what "√âvasion" means to you.



Consequently, in live mode, multiple options are available.

You can display the output with different pixel densities for a better resolution:

 - press [2] to display a 2000 x 2000 pixels output (display by default)
 - press [3] to display a 3000 x 3000 pixels output
 - press [4] to display a 4000 x 4000 pixels output (may take a moment)


You can also toggle different elements of the output, even though these features are not part of your mint:

 - press [d] to toggle the visibility of the dune
 - press [v] to toggle the visibility of the veils
 - press [t] to toggle the visibility of the sun texture
 - press [w] to toggle the visibility of the window shadow
 - press [a] to toggle the visibility of the sun rays
 - press [r] to reload


To save the output as it is displayed:

 - press [s] on a computer
 - double tap on a mobile device


On the contrary, some elements cannot be changed, such as the color palette, the place of the window and sun, the appearence of the dune, the texture, the format, etc.


Main features of this project include:

- Palette: 9 color palettes,
- Margin: Thin or Large,
- Texture: None, Soft or Strong,
- Format: 1:1, 4:5 - Portrait or 4:5 - Landscape,
- Veils: True or False,
- Rays: True or False,
- Sun Texture: True or False.


Thank you so much to all the collectors <3


Created with p5.js

metadata.name: Reading a book #602
metadata.description:
The formal structure of a book is beautiful by itself, but its aesthetic is the tacit atmosphere within which events take place in a story.

The WebGL real-time animation sets up an initial grid based on the fxhash. The grid cells get subdivided into another grid and the resulting cells become filled with pixels in color (~33%) or black and white (~66%).
The colored pixels come in 3 different coloring styles.
- Big Palette (~49%)
- Small Palette (~49%)
- Monochrome [b/w] (~2%)
4 noise algorithms modify the pixels of selected grid cells while at the same time 4 reset algorithms reassemble the initial image. The selected cells switch over time.

metadata.name: On the Road #32
metadata.description:
Adventure Road is printed and frozen with fading film slides from someone's archive.
The travel diary becomes an endless M√∂bius strip, spinning in circles like a wheel. How to stop coming back to it, rereading the notes in the margins of your life.

Aesthetically, I was inspired by Diango Hern√°ndez‚Äôs collage works and the book 'On the Road' by Jack Kerouac. This is a story about nomadism as lifestyle. 

Neural vintage photos are used as material for blobs. Exactly those, that are hardly distinguishable from each other, and which could be observed while driving a car along an endless highway.

Thanks to Yulikolay for helping with code, using p5.Riso.js library.
Source images are made with a help of DALL¬∑E mini neural network.
